What Factors Most Impact Student Performance?¶

By Andy Yan

Introduction¶

Education is one of the most important stages in a person's life. The knowledge we accumulate through our time in school helps us in our jobs and in dealing with everyday problems. We meet important people and organizations and make lasting relationships through the end of time. Unfortunately, for one reason or another, there are many young students out there who do not perform as well in school. Sometimes it is due to effort and the amount of work the student puts in, but oftentimes the reason is because of circumstances that are out of this person's control. Let's explore some of these circumstances and see how they correlate with a student's grades.

The purpose of this tutorial is to analyze many factors that contribute to student grades so that we can get a better understanding of what needs to be focused on to better help students around the world. Data science helps us analyze each factor and put a metric on which factor is the most impactful on student performance.

Data Collection¶

The data we use comes from Kaggle, an online platform where there are many datasets and resources for public use. I chose datasets that accumulated a lot of information about secondary (high school) students in two high schools in Portugal, as well as their grades. The information was collected using public information and asking surveys and questionnaires to the people involved. There are actually two datasets used in this tutorial. One is for the student's performance in Portuguese, while the other is for their performance in Math. The two datasets have the exact same columns and factors, but one problem is that the Math dataset has only 395 entries, while the Portuguese dataset has 695 entries. We could merge the two datasets together, but for simplicity's sake we will leave the datasets as is and analyze each one separately.

For more information about the datasets, you can go to https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/320/student+performance

Data Processing¶

In this section, we make use of Pandas to store the data into a dataframe and do analysis on the data. To learn more about Pandas and the functionality of this module, you can check out https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/index.html.

The datasets provided are pretty clean, as we don't have to worry about any missing values in the data. There are 33 columns total, which might seem like a lot, so let's go through each factor so we can better understand what the datasets can tell us.

Variables¶

  • school: For this dataset there are only two values since it only contains students from two schools. One of them is labeled 'GP', which stands for Gabriel Pereira and the other is 'MS', which stands for Mousinho da Silveira.
  • sex: There are two options: 'F' for female or 'M' for male.
  • age: The values range from 15 to 22. Even though secondary education only lasts for three years in Portugal (grades 10 to 12), there are likely many students here who had to repeat a grade or started school late.
  • address: This describes whether the student lives in an urban area, dicated as'U', or a rural area, dictated as'R'.
  • famsize: Describes the family size. 'LE3' means less than or equal to 3 while 'GT3' means greater than 3.
  • Pstatus: Describes the parent's living status. 'T' means they are living together and 'A' means they are living apart.
  • Medu: Describes the mother's education. 0 means none, 1 means primary education (up to 4th grade), 2 means 5th to 9th grade, 3 means secondary education and 4 means higher education).
  • Fedu: Describes the father's education with the same standards as for Medu.
  • Mjob: Describes the mother's job. The options are 'teacher', 'health', 'services', 'at_home' or 'other'.
  • Fjob: Describes the father's job. The options are the same as above.
  • reason: Describes the reason the student chose to go to school. The options are 'home', which means the school is close to their living quarters, 'reputation', 'course' or 'other'.
  • guardian: Describes the student's primary guardian. The options are 'mother', 'father' or 'other'.
  • traveltime: Describes how long it takes to travel to and from school. The options are 1, which is less than 15 minutes; 2, which is from 15 to 30 minutes; 3, which is from 30 minutes to 1 hour; or 4, which is more than 1 hour.
  • studytime: Describes the weekly study time. The options are 1, less than 2 hours; 2, from 2 to 5 hours; 3, from 5 to 10 hours; or 4, more than 10 hours.
  • failures: Describes how many classes this student has failed in the past. If it's 1, 2, or 3, it is labeled as such. However, any more is marked as 4 in the dataset.
  • schoolsup: Describes if the student is receiving any extra educational support. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • famsup: Describes if the student has family educational support. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • paid: Describes if the student is taking extra paid classes in the subject. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • activities: Describes if the student is taking any extra-curricular activities. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • nursery: Describes if the student attended nursery school. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • higher: Describes if the student wants to take higher education. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • internet: Describes if the student has internet access at home. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • romantic: Describes if the student is in a romantic relationship. The answer is either 'yes' or 'no'.
  • famrel: Describes the overall quality of the student's family relationships. This category is assigned a score from 1 to 5 where 1 is very bad and 5 is excellent.
  • freetime: Describes the amount of free time a student has after school. This category is assigned a score from 1 to 5 where 1 is very little time and 5 is a lot of time.
  • goout: Describes how often a student goes out with friends. This category is assigned a score from 1 to 5 where 1 is very little and 5 is a lot.
  • Dalc: Describes a student's alcohol consumption on school days. This category is assigned a score from 1 to 5 where 1 is very low and 5 is a lot.
  • Walc: Describes a student's alcohol consumption on weekends. This category is assigned a score from 1 to 5 where 1 is very low and 5 is a lot.
  • health: Describes a student's current health status. This category is assigned a score from 1 to 5 where 1 is very unhealthy and 5 is very healthy.
  • absences: Describes the total number of absences from school. The values range from 0 to 93.
  • G1: Describes the student's first period grade. The values range from 0 to 20.
  • G2: Describes the student's second period grade. The values range from 0 to 20.
  • G3: Describes the student's final grade. The values range from 0 to 20.

The last three columns are the dependent variables we are trying to explain, while the first 33 factors are the independent variables that attempt to explain the student's grades.

This next step is optional, but since the failures, paid, absences, G1, G2, and G3 columns in the Math and Portuguese datasets have the exact same names even though their values differ. In order to keep each dataset apart, we can rename the columns to be more specific so we can better differentiate between the two.

Exploratory analysis & Data viz¶

In order to get a better feel for the data it helps to plot out the data so we can better visualize it. We will be using matplotlib to accomplish this task. More information about this module can be found here at https://matplotlib.org/3.3.3/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.plot.html

Before we begin testing each individual factor, there is a slight issue in that there are three columns for grades, which are now labeled Portuguese (or Math) Grade 1, Portuguese (or Math) Grade 2, and Portuguese (or Math) Final Grade. First test to see the correlation between Grade 1 and the Final Grade and Grade 2 and the Final Grade by graphing a scatter plot. Then, we find the average of these two grades and see if that impacts the correlation between the period grades and the final grade.

In both the Portuguese and the Math case there appears to be a clear linear relationship between the period grades and the student's final grade. However, the problem is that period grades aren't really a factor, since what determines a student's grade is based on the other 33 columns. As a result, moving forward we will ignore Grades 1 and 2 and simply use the final grade for each subject as the dependent variable.

Here we create two functions that plot the mean and standard deviation of each factor against the dependent variable, which is the final grade, using a bar graph. The only difference between the two is that one is for the Portuguese dataset, while the other is for the Math dataset.

In [479]:
def plot_por_attribute(attribute):
                   
    plt.title('Final Portuguese Grades by ' + attribute)
    plt.xlabel(attribute)
    plt.ylabel('Final Grades')

    attributes = por_dataframe[attribute].unique()
    for att in attributes:
        filtered = por_dataframe[por_dataframe[attribute] == att]
        
        mean = filtered['Portuguese Final Grade'].mean()
        std = filtered['Portuguese Final Grade'].std()

        plt.bar(att, mean)
        plt.bar(att, std)

    plt.show()

def plot_math_attribute(attribute):
                   
    plt.title('Final Math Grades by ' + attribute)
    plt.xlabel(attribute)
    plt.ylabel('Final Grades')

    attributes = math_dataframe[attribute].unique()
    for att in attributes:
        filtered = math_dataframe[math_dataframe[attribute] == att]
        
        mean = filtered['Math Final Grade'].mean()
        std = filtered['Math Final Grade'].std()

        plt.bar(att, mean)
        plt.bar(att, std)

    plt.show()

Now we plot each factor from both datasets against the final grades so we can visually see which factor impacts the grade the most.

Analysis, hypothesis testing, & ML¶

That was a lot of factors, and just off a quick glance you might be able to tell which factor impacts the dependent variable the most. But in order to make sure, we have to do some analysis and train a machine learning algorithm to calculate a value that associates with a factor's impact. We will use linear regresion to accomplish this task.

First we replace all binary columns with 1s and 0s because linear regression requires that all the data be in numbers, not in categorical data. Then, we use statsmodels.formula.api's ols method to calculate all the statistics we need to determine which factor explains the data the most. We do this twice, one for each dataset. Find out more about the ols method here at https://www.statsmodels.org/stable/generated/statsmodels.formula.api.ols.html

In [527]:
por_dataframe.replace({"yes": 1, "no": 0, "GP": 1, "MS": 0, "M": 1, "F": 0}, inplace=True)
math_dataframe.replace({"yes": 1, "no": 0, "GP": 1, "MS": 0, "M": 1, "F": 0}, inplace=True)

formula = "Q('Portuguese Final Grade') ~ school + sex + age + address + famsize + Pstatus + Medu + Fedu + Mjob + \
reason + guardian + traveltime + studytime + Q('Failures Before Portuguese Class') + schoolsup + famsup + Q('Extra Paid Classes Within Portuguese') + \
activities + nursery + higher + internet + romantic + famrel + freetime + goout + Dalc + Walc + health + Q('Portuguese Absences')"
reg = smf.ols(formula=formula, data=por_dataframe).fit()
reg.summary()

Based off the R squared value, which tells you the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is explained by the independent variables in a regression model, we can already see that a lot of these factors are not good indicators for final grades, as the value is only 0.353 and 0.2666. In other words, only 35.3% and 26.66% of the variance in final grades is explained by the 33 other factors in the dataset. However, we are still able to tell which factors are likely to contribute the most to the dependent variable by looking at the p-value for each coefficient. If the p-value is less than 0.05 forae coefficient estimat,g the predictor variabl has a a significant effect othe final gradecyIn other words, we want to extract all the factors that have a p-value less than 0.5 to do further linear regression testing on. For the Portuguese dataset, the factors are school, sex, studytime, failures, schoolsup, desire to do higher education, and health. For the Math dataset, the factors are sex, failures, and romantic.

You can see that the factors for Math are significantly fewer compared to the factors for Portuguese. This could be because there is not enough data in the Math dataset, since there were only 395 values compared to 649. As a result, a lot of the data could be skewed or missing.

For our machine learning, we will use linear regression on these factors picked above and determine the coefficient for determination for each one to see which factor explains the final grade the best. The function below separates the data passed in into training and testing sets. We use the training sets to train the model to find the least squares regression line that best matches the data, and then use this line to predict it on the testing data. We then calculate a coefficient of determination to see how well the linear regression line matches the testing data. We use the sklearn's linear_model library to accomplish this. You can learn more about it here at https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.htmlent.

In [528]:
def linear_regression(X, Y):
    X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=0.2)
    model.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_predict = model.predict(X_test)

    r_squared = model.score(X_test, Y_test)
    print('Coefficients: ', model.coef_[0])
    print('Intercept: ', model.intercept_)
    print(f"Coefficient of Determination: {r_squared}")

    plt.scatter(X, Y)
    plt.plot(X_test, Y_predict, color = 'black')
    plt.show()

Interpretation: Insight & Conclusions¶

For the Portuguese dataset, the two factors with the highest coefficient of determination are 'Failures Before Portuguese Class' and 'health. They had a coefficient of 0.15720827291449457 and 0.10990277446555308. For the math dataset, the best factor by far was the 'Failures Before Math Class', which had a coefficient of determination of 0.2070231183430309.

Based off these results alone, it would seem that a student having previous failures in other classes would have the biggest impact on their grade as for both datasets, this factor had the highest coefficient of determination. However, we cannot say for sure. We only performed our linear regression training algorithm on these two datasets once, which isn't enough to fully determine whether these results are accurate. In order to achieve greater accuracy, we could've run the algorithm using multiple different training and testing sets and recalculating the coefficient of determination each time. Also, we should keep in mind that our dataset only took students from two high schools in Portugal, which is not representative of all high school students worldwide. However, this was just a basic dive into a highly complex subject with a myriad of factors, and with further time and resources spent developing this project, we may be able to generalize our results to a bigger population.
